{"key":"post-10258853","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10258853</id>\n<content>Never make a casing layer OR bulk substrate without gypsum.&amp;nbsp; It adds dramatically to the performance and weight of your flushes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gypsum isn't a pH buffer.&amp;nbsp; It doesn't alter pH to a noticeable degree.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gypsum supplies calcium and sulfur, both essential elements for good fruit body formation.&amp;nbsp; It also keeps the substrate or casing layer loose.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You don't really even want a 'long term buffer' such as limestone in a casing layer.&amp;nbsp; The life of a casing is measured in weeks, not months or years.&amp;nbsp; I recommend the use of hydrated lime to get an &lt;i&gt;immediate&lt;/i&gt; pH correction.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If your properly pasteurized casing layer is contaminating before first flush, it sounds like your spawn is contaminated.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're growing cubensis on a bulk substrate, no casing layer is needed, and not much will be gained from using one.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10259225</next>\n<prev>10258668</prev>\n<first>10257513</first>\n<last>14923768</last>\n<when>1241062222</when>\n<utime>04/30/09 06:30 AM</utime>\n</post>"}